gs":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"la","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Vietnamese Hung, Cuong, Anh, Thanh, Ha, Hoang, Tuan, Chau, Hao, Hien, Hoa, Hue, Nam, Phong, Sinh, Tuong, Min, Tam, Tanh, Thai, Tham, Tinh, Yeong.  Chinese Hong, Hang, Sang, Tong, Chan, Chi, Hwa Ja, Hyung, Kam, Ki Bong, Kin, Man.","Vietnamese: from the Chinese surname 羅, see   Luo   1.","Vietnamese (<b>Lã</b>): from the Chinese surname 呂, see   Lu   6 and 3 below."],"variants":[{"name":"Luo","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Wei, Jian, Yi, Ping, Yong, Zhen, Feng, Hong, Ming, Jin, Bin, Chen, Hai, Lan, Min, Huan, Hung, Shen, Tian.","Chinese:","Mandarin form of the surname 羅, meaning ‘net for catching birds’ or ‘to collect’ in Chinese: (i) from Luo (羅), the name of an ancient state (located in present-day Hubei province). After it was annexed by the state of Chu during the early Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ), people from the state migrated southwards and adopted Luo (羅) as their surname. (ii) from the Po Duo Luo (破多羅) and Chi Luo (叱羅) families from the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China, who changed their original surnames to 羅 during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD ). (iii) from the personal name Hu Se Luo (斛瑟羅), leader of an ancient Turkic tribe who are believed to have migrated to China during the Tang dynasty (618–907  AD ). His descendants inherited his name Hu Se Luo (斛瑟羅) as their surname and shortened it to 羅 during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD ). (iv) from the name of one of the seven families from the Bandun Man, an ethnic group residing in ancient southwestern China (located mainly in present-day Sichuan province)."]}]},{"name":"Mare","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Americo, Cesareo, Fernando, Ines, Javier, Jose, Marcos.  Portuguese Henrique.  Italian Antonio, Gino, Olindo, Silvio, Vito.  Dutch Andries.","Italian: topographic name for someone living by the sea, from <i>mare</i> ‘sea’.","English: variant of   Mear  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Marucci","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Rocco, Antonio, Silvio, Angelo, Carmela, Domenic, Donato, Egidio, Guido, Licinio, Lorenzo, Luciano.","Italian: patronymic or plural form of the personal name <i>Maruccio</i>, a pet form of   Mare   or   Mari  ."]},{"name":"Marelli","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Rocco, Giuseppe, Angelo, Dante.","Italian:","patronymic or plural form of a diminutive of   Mare  ."]},{"name":"Mear","meanings":["English: variant of   Mear  ."]}]},{"name":"Philip","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Greek name <i>Philippos</i>, meaning ‘lover of horses’, from <i>philein</i> ‘to love’ + <i>hippos</i> ‘horse’. This was popular in the classical period and since. It was the name of the father of  Alexander the Great . It was also the name of one of Christ's apostles, of a deacon ordained by the apostles after the death of Christ, and of several other early saints.  See also  Philippa ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":35,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Philip de la Mare was born about 1347, in Nunney, Somerset, England, his father, John De La Mare, was 19 and his mother, Margaret de Norton, was 15. He had at least 1 son and 2 daughters with Lady Matilda Hussey. He died in 1396, in his hometown, at the age of 50."},"et":{"about 1347–1396":"umbes 1347–1396","1347–1396":"1347–1396","1358–1420":"1358–1420","1359–1396":"1359–1396","1368–Female":"1368–Surnud","1374–1413":"1374–1413","1380–Male":"1380–Surnud","1384–1450":"1384–1450","1329–1389":"1329–1389","1333–Female":"1333–Surnud","abt 1380":"umbes 1380","1374":"1374","1396":"1396","1384":"1384","1450":"1450","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","1359":"1359","1413":"1413","1358":"1358","1347":"1347","1346":"1346","1368":"1368","1389":"1389","1333":"1333","about 1347":"umbes 1347","1420":"1420","1329":"1329","Monney Castle, Monney, Somerset, England":"Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England","Nunney, Somerset, England":"Nunney, Somerset, England","Nunney Castle, Frome, Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Nunney, Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","of Nunney, Som., Eng.":"Nunney, Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1347–1396":"noin 1347–1396","1347–1396":"1347–1396","1358–1420":"1358–1420","1359–1396":"1359–1396","1368–Female":"1368–Kuollut","1374–1413":"1374–1413","1380–Male":"1380–Kuollut","1384–1450":"1384–1450","1329–1389":"1329–1389","1333–Female":"1333–Kuollut","abt 1380":"noin 1380","1374":"1374","1396":"1396","1384":"1384","1450":"1450","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","1359":"1359","1413":"1413","1358":"1358","1347":"1347","1346":"1346","1368":"1368","1389":"1389","1333":"1333","about 13